\section{Introduction}

Silicon photonics is a technology that is becoming competitive with alternative technologies in photonics, being its high integrability and low cost the most appealing features. Nonlinear silicon photonics is a very active research line, as devices with all-optical functionality could boost their speed with respect to their electrically-controlled counterpart. Many different nonlinear devices have been reported in the last years, such as all-optical modulators,~\cite{Almeida2004a} wavelength converters,~\cite{Lee2009}, etc. All of them can be easily integrated into new devices within a small area thanks to the high refractive index of silicon. 

%All of them can be easily integrated into new devices within a small area thanks to the high refractive index of silicon. However such optical devices have been limited by the carrier dispersion and absorption effects, with a recombination time in the order of nanoseconds. Therefore, when carriers are generated they hinder all-optical devices speed below Gb/s.


%This could boost the speed of new devices working at low powers at which few carriers are generated.

%However such optical devices have been limited by the carrier dispersion and absorption effects, with a recombination time in the order of nanoseconds

%All-optical switches require a figure of merit higher than one to achieve a $2\pi$ phase shift, where the figure of merit is the ratio between the nonlinear coefficient and $4\pi$ times the nonlinear losses \cite{Mizrahi1989}. Several materials and structures with their figures of merit were shown in paper \cite{Koos2007}.

%Silicon photonics is a technology that is becoming competitive with alternative technologies in photonics, being its high integrability and low cost the most appealing features. Nonlinear silicon photonics is a very active research line, as devices with all-optical functionality could boost their speed with respect to their electrically-controlled counterpart. Many different nonlinear devices have been reported in the last years, such as all-optical modulators,~\cite{Almeida2004a} wavelength converters,~\cite{Lee2009}, etc. All of them can be easily integrated into new devices within a very small area, thanks to the high refractive index of silicon. However such optical devices have been limited by the carrier dispersion and absorption effects, with a recombination time in the order of nanoseconds, hindering possible all-optical devices to speeds under the Gb/s required in high-end systems. In all-optical switches, a figure of merit of 1 is needed for a $2\pi$ phase shift, defining the figure of merit as the ratio between the nonlinear coefficient and $4\pi$ times the nonlinear losses \cite{Mizrahi1989}. Several materials and structures with their figures of merit are shown in paper \cite{Koos2007}.


Amorphous silicon has been demonstrated to have a high nonlinear coefficient \cite{Narayanan2010} and low TPA thanks to its wider band-gap \cite{OLeary1997}. Moreover it is a material that can be easily grown in CMOS compatible processes. As it doesn't need to pass through high annealing temperatures it is a good candidate for all-optical interconnects in between different chips and it could be grown on a top layer not affecting circuits already integrated on the chip.

In paper \cite{Narayanan2010} a $Re\{\gamma\} = 2003 (W\cdot m)^{-1}$ nonlinear coefficient was presented, but the two photon absorption was also high, leading a figure of merit of 0.66, which is slightly higher than SOI waveguides. Different processing in the amorphous silicon grow has allowed to obtain a low TPA coefficient and the highest figure of merit of a CMOS-compatible photonic waveguide.



%Paper \cite{Narayanan2010} obtains a nonlinear coefficient $Re\{\gamma\} = 2003 (W\cdot m)^{-1}$ but as it showed also a high two photon absorption coefficient, the figure of merit is 0.66, which is slightly higher than SOI waveguides. In this paper we obtain the same TPA coefficient both for an amorphous silicon TM waveguide and silicon strip SOI waveguide. However the nonlinear coefficient is 7 times larger, with figure of merit for a CMOS-compatible photonic waveguide.


%A figure of merit is defined in paper \cite{Mizrahi1989} for all-optical switching devices, stating that a figure of merit of 1 is needed for a phase shift of $2\pi$rad. 
%Not needing high annealing temperatures as in crystalline silicon would be a good candidate for all-optical interconnects in between different chips
%Moreover it does not ne
%In paper \cite{Koos2007} a two photon absorption figure of merit is defined the the 
%When carrier effects are involved in these devices, the speed is limited by the carrier recombination time, which is usually in the order of 1ns. Although carrier sweeping can improve the speed,~\cite{Turner-Foster2010} nonlinear devices based on bound-electron Kerr effect are preferred, as their bandwidth does not have this limitation. One interesting parameter is the nonlinear absorption coefficient.
%An easy way to determine the figure of merit of a waveguide
%Slot waveguides have demonstrated to increase the Kerr effect because of the field enhancement produced in the low-index section. Different materials have been used to fill the slot, such as organic polymers, which have allowed to demonstrate all-optical 160Gb/s demultiplexing,~\cite{Koos2009} but these materials involve non-CMOS processes and impose temperature limitations. Silicon-nanocrystal-based waveguides are fully CMOS-compatible and have a very high nonlinear coefficient,~\cite{Spano2009} and ultrafast all-optical modulation and logic gates have been recently demonstrated \cite{Martinez2010a}-\cite{Otona}. In this paper we study the nonlinear dynamics of this kind of waveguides with a time-resolved technique and we also report four-wave-mixing measurements that provide a complete nonlinear characterization.
